  <static seed="1450" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalEquations/solveRationalEquations25.pg">
    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {\frac{r}{5r+15}+\frac{5}{r+3}}={-2}  }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="31" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{-5\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To clear fractions in an equation, multiply each side of the equation by a common denominator. For this problem, a common denominator is <m>{5\mathopen{}\left(r+3\right)}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
  {\frac{r}{5r+15}+\frac{5}{r+3}} \amp = {-2} \\
  {\frac{r}{5\mathopen{}\left(r+3\right)}+\frac{5}{r+3}} \amp = {-2} \\
  {\frac{r}{5\mathopen{}\left(r+3\right)}\cdot 5\mathopen{}\left(r+3\right)+\frac{5}{r+3}\cdot 5\mathopen{}\left(r+3\right)} \amp = {-10\mathopen{}\left(r+3\right)} \\
  {r+25} \amp = {-10r-30} \\
  {r+10r} \amp = {-30-25} \\
  {11r} \amp = {-55} \\
  \frac{{11r}}{11} \amp = \frac{{-55}}{11} \\
  r \amp = -5
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must check solutions when we solve rational equations. In the original equation, both denominators cannot be <m>0</m>. We set them to <m>0</m>, so we can find out what values to exclude from the solution set.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \amp 5r+15 = 0 \amp \;\amp  r+3=0 \\
   \amp 5r = -15 \amp \;\amp  r=-3 \\
   \amp \frac{5r}{5} = \frac{-15}{5} \\
   \amp r = -3 \\
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must exclude <m>-3</m> from the solution set. This value is not in the solution set we got, so the final solution is <m>r=-5</m>.</p>
</solution>
